Yes.

Visualization is only one narrow form of re-experiencing.

When humans re-experience something, we can partially reactivate many layers of the original state:

* Sensory (what you saw, heard, smelled, tasted, felt)
* Emotional (how it felt)
* Physiological (heart rate, tension, breathing)
* Narrative (what it meant)
* Attentional (what stood out)
* Motor (how your body was prepared to act)
* Relational (who was there and how you felt about them)
* Identity (who you believed yourself to be in that moment)

A memory is less like a video recording and more like a compressed state package.

When you “remember” your first jump, a deployment, a golf shot, holding your son for the first time, or a difficult conversation, you aren’t merely replaying images.

You’re partially reconstructing an entire configuration of mind and body.

This is why:

* Thinking about a lemon can make your mouth water.
* A song can transport you back twenty years.
* Smelling jet fuel or ocean air can bring back an entire chapter of life.
* Remembering an embarrassing moment can make you cringe in the present.

The body often doesn’t distinguish perfectly between direct experience and sufficiently vivid reconstruction.

What’s interesting is that this connects to what you’ve been circling around with recall.

Most people treat memory as storage.

But memory is often more usefully understood as state re-entry.

The question becomes:

Can I intentionally re-enter the useful parts of a prior state without carrying all the baggage attached to it?

A golfer doesn’t need every memory from the last round.

He needs access to:

* the calm state,
* the rhythm,
* the confidence,
* the feel of a good swing.

A SEAL doesn’t need every detail of training.

He needs access to:

* composure,
* focus,
* disciplined action under pressure.

A father doesn’t need every memory of every day with his children.

He needs access to:

* love,
* patience,
* perspective,
    when it matters.

That starts looking a lot like the recall doctrine you’ve been developing:

Archive → Handle → Invocation → Action

The goal isn’t to remember everything.

The goal is to be able to become the version of yourself that knew what was needed when the moment calls for it.

In that framing, memory becomes less about possession and more about navigation.

Not:

“How do I keep everything?”

But:

“How do I reliably return to the state I need?”

That is a different problem entirely—and often a much more tractable one.